      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
			<head>Biographical History</head>
			<p>Margaret Bourke-White (1904-1971) was an American photographer, war correspondent, author and photojournalist.  Among her many achievements, she was the first foreign photographer allowed to take pictures in the USSR of Soviet industry, the first female war correspondent, and the first female photographer for <emph render="italic">Life</emph> magazine, where her work appeared on the cover of the magazine's first issue.    She was the author of more than ten books, including her autobiography <emph render="italic">Portrait of Myself</emph> (1963).   She received numerous awards over her career, including honorary doctorates from Rutgers University and the University of Michigan, and in 1997 she was designated a Women's History Month honoree by the National Women's History Project.</p>
		</bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">Margaret Bourke-White Collection</emph> is a supplementary collection, created by &scrc_name;, containing material relating to Bourke-White, but acquired by &scrc_name; separately from the Margaret Bourke-White Papers, through purchase or gift.  The collection consists primarily of reproductions made for exhibits or other purposes (and thus duplicates original material in the Margaret Bourke-White Papers), although there are a few video recordings and some original production stills from the movie <emph render="italic">North Star</emph>.  Quantities other than 1 are given in parentheses.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      
